What I’m really looking for is an approach, an assessment skill set I can use to evaluate that business, and then potential roadmap options they can implement to start using AI.21 AprClaude responded: This is a great question, and it's a situation you'll encounter a lot — legacy systems, no integrations, tight budgets.This is a great question, and it's a situation you'll encounter a lot — legacy systems, no integrations, tight budgets. The good news is that AI adoption doesn't require rebuilding their stack. Let me walk you through an approach you can use as a repeatable framework.
The core principle
For a cost-sensitive business with 10+ year-old systems and no integrations, you're not selling "AI transformation." You're selling augmentation around the edges — using AI where it doesn't need to touch their core systems at all. The legacy stack stays untouched; AI works on the inputs and outputs that humans are already handling manually.
This reframing matters because it changes the conversation from "expensive multi-year modernization" to "small, reversible experiments that pay for themselves."
A three-phase approach
Phase 1 — Discovery & Value Mapping (2–3 weeks)
The goal here isn't to audit their IT. It's to find the 3–5 highest-pain, highest-volume human workflows that surround their legacy systems. These are the places where staff re-key data, read long documents, draft the same emails repeatedly, or manually classify things. AI adds value here without needing any integration.
Phase 2 — Pilot (6–10 weeks, one use case)
Pick one use case with clear ROI, low risk, and no system integration required. Build it as a standalone tool — a web app, a chat interface, a shared inbox assistant. Prove value with real numbers (hours saved, error rate reduction) before expanding.
Phase 3 — Scale & Roadmap (ongoing)
Once the pilot proves value, sequence 3–5 more use cases over 12–18 months. Only consider deeper integration work once the business has confidence and a track record.
Assessment skill set
When you walk in to evaluate a business like this, here's what you're actually looking at:
Process discovery & observation. Shadow staff for a few hours. Watch what they do between systems — that's where the opportunity lives. Look for copy-paste patterns, document reading, email triage, manual classification, report generation from raw data.
Document & data inventory. Not database schemas — you're looking at unstructured content: emails, PDFs, contracts, invoices, meeting notes, customer queries. This is AI's sweet spot and it bypasses the integration problem entirely.
Volumetrics & pain quantification. How many invoices per week? How long does a quote take to produce? How many customer emails does support handle? You need numbers to build an ROI case a cost-sensitive owner will accept.
Change-readiness assessment. Who are the likely champions? Who's threatened? Is there at least one tech-comfortable person on staff who can own the tool day-to-day? Without this, even a perfect pilot fails.
Risk & compliance scan. What data is sensitive? Are they in a regulated industry? This shapes whether you recommend cloud AI APIs, a private deployment, or a hybrid.
Commercial literacy. Understanding their revenue model well enough to translate "saves 8 hours a week" into dollars they care about.
Roadmap options — three tiers
Here are three patterns you can offer, scaled to different risk appetites and budgets:
Tier 1 — "AI as a smart assistant" (lowest cost, fastest value)
The team uses off-the-shelf AI tools (Claude, ChatGPT, Copilot) with light customization. You provide prompt libraries, templates, and training. No integration, no custom development. Think: drafting proposals, summarizing long documents, researching prospects, cleaning up meeting notes. Timeline: 4–6 weeks. Cost: licensing plus a small advisory fee. This is often the right starting point — it builds AI literacy before you spend on custom builds.
Tier 2 — "Standalone AI tools" (moderate cost, higher value)
Build one or two lightweight custom tools that sit alongside the legacy systems. A user uploads a document or pastes text, the AI processes it, the user pastes the result back into their system of record. Examples: an invoice data extractor, a contract clause reviewer, a customer email classifier with draft replies, a quote generator from a product catalogue. Timeline: 8–12 weeks per tool. Cost: moderate build cost plus ongoing API usage (usually quite small).
Tier 3 — "Lightweight integration" (higher cost, compounding value)
Only after Tier 1 or 2 has proved value. Use RPA, file watchers, or simple export/import scripts to connect the AI tools to the legacy systems without modifying those systems. An AI agent reads the nightly export, produces output, drops it into a shared folder or emails it to the right person. Timeline: 3–6 months. Cost: higher but still far below an integration or replacement project.
How to pitch this to a cost-sensitive client
A few framing moves that tend to land well:
Lead with a fixed-price discovery engagement (Phase 1) as a standalone deliverable. They get a prioritised roadmap with ROI estimates even if they don't proceed. Low commitment, high perceived value.
Promise that the pilot will either pay for itself within 12 months or you'll identify the reason clearly. Cost-sensitive clients need to see a payback period they can underwrite.
Explicitly tell them you're not recommending they replace their systems. That's often what they're afraid you'll say, and getting it off the table early changes the tone of the whole conversation.
Use the language of "experiments" rather than "projects." Experiments are small, reversible, and their failure is information. Projects are big and scary.

