The reference architecture
At its simplest, a standalone AI tool has five layers:

User interface — where staff interact with the tool
Application logic — orchestration, business rules, workflow
AI/LLM layer — the model doing the thinking
Data layer — storage for documents, embeddings, history, audit logs
Input/output bridges — how data gets in and out without touching legacy systems

You don't need exotic tech for any of this. The whole point of this pattern is that modern AI tooling has matured enough that a small team can stand up production-grade tools quickly.
Recommended default stack
This is what I'd reach for first for most SME clients in the Tier 2 scenario:
Frontend / UI

Next.js (React) or Streamlit for internal tools
Streamlit is remarkable for internal business tools — a single Python file can give you a working app with file uploads, forms, and data display. For a cost-sensitive client where only internal staff use the tool, it's often the right answer.
Next.js when you need a more polished UX, external users, or richer interactivity.

Backend / application logic

Python with FastAPI — the default for anything AI-heavy. The ecosystem (LangChain, LlamaIndex, pypdf, pandas) is Python-first.
Node.js with Express or Next.js API routes if the team is JavaScript-oriented.

AI / LLM layer

Anthropic Claude API or OpenAI API for general reasoning, document understanding, drafting, classification.
Claude tends to be stronger for long documents, careful reasoning, and business writing; worth benchmarking both on the actual use case.
For embeddings (semantic search, document retrieval): OpenAI text-embedding-3 or Voyage AI.
For sensitive data where cloud APIs are off the table: Ollama running Llama 3, Mistral, or Qwen on a local server. Performance is lower but acceptable for many back-office tasks.

Orchestration framework (optional but useful)

LangChain or LlamaIndex for document processing, RAG patterns, and chaining calls.
Honest caveat: for simple use cases, direct API calls are often cleaner than pulling in a framework. Only reach for these when you're doing retrieval over a document corpus or building multi-step agents.

Data layer

PostgreSQL for structured data, conversation history, audit logs.
pgvector (Postgres extension) for embeddings — avoids adding a separate vector database for most SME workloads.
Pinecone, Weaviate, or Qdrant if the document volume is large or you need dedicated vector DB features.
S3 / Azure Blob / Cloudflare R2 for document storage.

Input/output bridges (the critical piece for legacy-system clients)

Shared folders (SharePoint, Google Drive, Dropbox) — staff drop files in, AI processes, results land in an "output" folder.
Email ingestion — a dedicated inbox the AI monitors; outputs go back by reply. Surprisingly effective.
CSV import/export — legacy systems almost all support CSV. Scheduled exports feed the AI; outputs are re-imported manually or via script.
RPA tools (UiPath, Power Automate, n8n) when you need to bridge to a system with no API — n8n is the cost-sensitive favourite, open source and self-hostable.

Authentication

Microsoft Entra ID (Azure AD) if they're a Microsoft 365 shop — almost always the path of least resistance.
Auth0 or Clerk for simpler standalone setups.

Hosting

Azure App Service or Azure Container Apps — natural fit if the client uses Microsoft 365, and the enterprise procurement story is easier.
AWS (ECS Fargate, Lambda, or Lightsail) for more flexibility.
Vercel for Next.js frontends.
A single VPS (Hetzner, DigitalOcean) for the truly cost-sensitive — $20–50/month hosts a surprising amount.

Observability & cost control

Langfuse or Helicone for LLM call logging, cost tracking, and debugging prompts. Underrated — you need this from day one or you'll have no idea why costs are what they are.
Sentry for application errors.

Three concrete stack examples
Let me make this tangible with three use cases:
Example 1: Invoice data extraction tool
Staff drop PDF invoices into a SharePoint folder. Extracted data appears in a CSV they can import into the legacy accounting system.
Stack: Python + FastAPI backend running on Azure Container Apps, polling SharePoint via Microsoft Graph API. PDFs processed with Claude (vision capability handles scanned invoices). Extracted fields validated against a schema, written to a CSV in an output folder. PostgreSQL logs every extraction for audit. Streamlit dashboard for staff to review low-confidence extractions.
Example 2: Customer email triage and draft replies
A shared inbox monitored by the tool. Each incoming email is classified, tagged, and a suggested reply is drafted. Staff review and send.
Stack: Python service connecting to the inbox via IMAP or Microsoft Graph. Claude classifies and drafts responses using a prompt library plus examples of past good replies (few-shot). Responses written back as draft replies in the same inbox. No UI needed — staff work entirely in their existing email client.
Example 3: Proposal generator from product catalogue
Sales staff fill a form describing a client opportunity. The tool generates a draft proposal drawing from the product catalogue and past proposals.
Stack: Next.js frontend for the form and generated output. FastAPI backend. Product catalogue and past proposals embedded with OpenAI embeddings, stored in pgvector. Claude generates the draft using retrieved relevant content. Output is a Word doc staff can download and polish. Hosted on Vercel + a small Azure Postgres instance.
A few principles worth stating
Start with the simplest stack that could possibly work. A Streamlit app calling the Claude API with file upload is a legitimate production tool for many use cases, and you can ship it in days.
Defer infrastructure decisions. Don't spend week one choosing between Pinecone and Weaviate — use pgvector until you have a reason to change.
Budget for LLM costs explicitly. A rough rule: assume $0.01–$0.10 per interaction for document-heavy use cases with Claude. Track it from day one. For most SMEs, total monthly API cost is well under what they'd pay a single staff member for the hours saved.
Log everything. Every prompt, every response, every user action. You cannot improve what you cannot see, and you'll need this data to demonstrate ROI.
Plan for the model changing. Wrap LLM calls in your own abstraction so you can swap providers. Models improve every few months and prices drop — you want to capture that upside.

