Why screen recording will backfire
Legal and regulatory exposure. In Singapore (where CPF sits), the PDPA requires clear notification and purpose limitation. In Australia, state surveillance laws (especially NSW, Victoria, WA) require explicit written consent for workplace monitoring and in some cases a formal surveillance policy published in advance. In the EU, GDPR plus works council requirements make this very hard. Even where it's legal, doing it wrong creates liability that dwarfs any consulting fee.
Trust destruction. The moment staff learn their screens are being recorded "to help with AI," two things happen: they assume AI is coming for their jobs, and they stop behaving normally. You'll capture theatre, not work. Worse, the champions you need for adoption — the curious finance analyst, the tech-comfortable warehouse 2IC — are exactly the people most likely to feel betrayed and become blockers.
Data you can't use. Screen recordings capture customer PII, payment details, HR data, health information, confidential contracts. The moment you record it, you inherit a data protection problem. Storing it, analysing it, and getting AI to process it all become regulated activities. For a cost-sensitive SME, the compliance overhead alone kills the project.
Signal-to-noise is terrible. A week of screen recording for one person is maybe 40 hours of video. Multiply by 10 people and you have 400 hours of footage to analyse. Even with AI doing the analysis, you'll spend more time processing recordings than you would running good observation sessions.
It signals the wrong thing about your firm. Thakral One walking into a client and proposing surveillance to design AI solutions is a brand problem. Clients will wonder what else you'd do with their data.
What you actually want — and how to get it
Strip away the mechanism and the underlying idea is excellent: systematically capture roles and tasks so you can map AI opportunities against real work, not imagined work. That's a genuinely valuable methodology. Here are the ways to do it that actually work.
Structured work observation (ethnographic method). Sit next to someone for half a day with their permission and a clear brief. Take notes on what they do, what systems they switch between, where they pause, what frustrates them. This is the gold standard and it's what management consultancies charge a fortune for. Four hours with a finance clerk will tell you more than a week of screen recordings, because a trained observer is filtering for the right signals in real time.
Task diaries. Give each participant a simple template — a Google Form or a Notion page — and ask them to log tasks in 15- or 30-minute blocks for one week. "What did you do, what systems did you use, what was frustrating, what felt like wasted time." Staff do this willingly when framed as "help us find ways to make your job easier." You get self-reported data that's directionally accurate and comes with their own commentary on pain points.
Process walkthroughs with artifacts. Ask the warehouse manager to walk you through a typical receiving workflow, with actual paperwork, actual screens, actual emails in front of them. Record the session (with consent) rather than their ongoing work. One hour of this per key process gives you extraordinary insight and it's a collaborative activity, not surveillance.
The "show me your inbox" technique. Ask to sit with someone and have them walk through their last 20 emails and what each one required of them. Same for their last 20 tasks in their task list, or their last 10 calls. You'll spot repetitive patterns within the first five examples.
Consented, voluntary time-tracking tools. Tools like Toggl, RescueTime, or Timely let the user themselves see where their time goes, and they can opt to share aggregated, redacted summaries with you. This flips the dynamic — it becomes a tool for the employee to understand their own work, and you get access to the output. RescueTime in particular uses AI to categorise activity and can produce role-level summaries without exposing individual content.
AI-assisted meeting and call observation. Tools like Fireflies, Otter, or Gong capture meetings and calls with consent. These often reveal organisational bottlenecks — what gets discussed repeatedly, where decisions stall, which handoffs break down. Much richer signal than screen captures of individual work.
The methodology you're actually reaching for
Here's the framework I think you're circling around. Call it a Role & Task AI Opportunity Map. It has three phases:
Phase 1 — Role decomposition. For each key role, break the job into 8–15 recurring tasks. Not "manage the warehouse" but "receive inbound shipments," "resolve stock discrepancies," "respond to supplier delivery queries," "produce weekly stock report." Get this from a structured interview plus one observation session per role. A half-day per role is usually enough.
Phase 2 — Task characterisation. For each task, capture: frequency (daily/weekly/monthly), time per instance, inputs (what information comes in and from where), outputs (what gets produced and for whom), systems touched, judgment required, and pain level (a simple 1–5 from the person doing it). This becomes a structured dataset you can analyse.
Phase 3 — AI mapping. Now you can systematically evaluate each task against AI suitability criteria: Is it language-heavy? Pattern-based? Does it involve reading documents or drafting content? Is the input unstructured and the output structured (or vice versa)? Does it require reasoning over context that could be pre-loaded? Score each task and you get a prioritised opportunity list per role, with frequency × time saved × pain giving you a rough ROI indicator.
This is what you present back to the client as a deliverable. It's a map — they can see every task, why it was or wasn't recommended for AI, and what the implementation pattern would be. It's defensible, it's collaborative, and it's reusable across clients as a Thakral One methodology.
The deeper point
The reason this framing is stronger than screen recording is that it treats staff as partners in identifying opportunities rather than subjects of study. The warehouse manager knows where the pain is. The finance clerk knows which reports are pointless. The sales rep knows which admin tasks eat their selling time. Your job as an advisor isn't to extract knowledge from them covertly — it's to give them a structured way to surface what they already know, and then to translate that into an AI opportunity assessment they couldn't do themselves.
That's a service worth paying for. Surveillance isn't.
