The framing principle
Business leaders don't need to understand how AI works. They need to understand what it is in their world, what it changes, and what they need to put around it to make it work. Three questions, in that order.
The mistake most pitches make is spending too long on question one (what AI is) and not enough on questions two and three. Leaders accept a clear definition quickly and move on. What they actually want is the implications.
Part 1 — What AI is, for a business leader
Here's a definition that works in the room:

"AI is software that can read, write, decide, and predict the way a capable employee can — but at the speed and scale of a computer. It doesn't replace judgment; it handles the parts of knowledge work that are repetitive, pattern-based, or volume-constrained."

Then you break it into four capabilities they can recognise from their own business:
1. AI that reads. It ingests documents, emails, contracts, reports, images, recordings, and makes sense of them. The business equivalent of a junior analyst who can read 500 pages overnight and tell you what matters. Examples: extracting data from supplier invoices, summarising long contracts, classifying customer complaints, reading CVs against job descriptions.
2. AI that writes. It drafts documents, emails, reports, proposals, and code. The equivalent of a capable writer who produces a first draft in seconds that a human then refines. Examples: drafting monthly variance commentary, writing proposal sections, generating customer responses, producing board papers.
3. AI that decides. It classifies, routes, recommends, and flags. The equivalent of an experienced triage person who knows what goes where and what needs escalation. Examples: categorising expenses, routing customer tickets to the right team, flagging anomalous transactions, prioritising sales leads.
4. AI that predicts. It forecasts, scores, and projects based on patterns in data. The equivalent of an analyst with perfect recall of every historical pattern. Examples: demand forecasting, churn prediction, credit scoring, maintenance scheduling.
Every AI use case in their business is going to be some combination of these four capabilities. Once a leader sees this, they start spotting opportunities on their own — which is exactly what you want in a sales conversation.
