Part 2 — The value AI provides, in business terms
Don't lead with productivity percentages. Lead with the five ways AI shows up on a P&L or in a strategic conversation. These are the outcomes leaders actually care about:
1. Labour leverage. The same team accomplishes more, or a smaller team accomplishes the same. This is the most common and most tangible value. Real number: well-targeted AI deployment typically reclaims 20–40% of time on targeted tasks. Not 20–40% of a person's job — 20–40% of the specific tasks AI is applied to.
2. Speed to outcome. Things that took days take hours. Things that took hours take minutes. The value isn't just the time saved — it's what becomes possible when cycle times collapse. A finance team that closes the books in three days instead of eight makes better decisions four days earlier, every month.
3. Consistency and quality at scale. Every proposal reflects best practice. Every customer response is on-brand. Every invoice is coded correctly. AI reduces the gap between your best performer and your average performer. This is enormous in businesses where quality variance costs money.
4. Capability access. The business gets capabilities it couldn't previously afford. A small business now has access to what amounts to a research analyst, a copywriter, a data analyst, and a legal reviewer — for the cost of a software subscription. This reframes AI from "cost reduction" to "capability expansion," which is a stronger value narrative for growing businesses.
5. Risk reduction. Fewer errors, better compliance, earlier detection of problems. Quantified as cost-of-error avoided, regulatory exposure reduced, or insurance claims avoided. This is how you sell AI into regulated industries and risk-averse buyers.
The framing: "AI creates value in five ways. Every engagement we do targets one or two of these explicitly, with a measurement attached. We don't pitch 'AI transformation' because that's not a number you can manage. We pitch 'eight hours a week returned to your finance team' or 'error rate reduced from 3% to under 1%.' Those you can manage."
Part 3 — What the business needs to put around AI to make it work
