That's a fundamentally different sales conversation and a much bigger engagement.
The AI Maturity Model — five stages
Here's the arc that works. Five stages, each defined by what AI is doing in the business and what that unlocks.
Stage 1 — AI as Assistant
What it looks like: Individual employees use AI tools (Claude, Copilot, ChatGPT) to help with their own work. The AI responds to prompts. A human initiates every interaction, reviews every output, and decides what to do with it.
Value created: Personal productivity. Time reclaimed at the individual level. Better quality outputs from average performers.
What the business needs: Licenses, basic training, prompt libraries, acceptable-use policy.
Limitations: Value is trapped at the individual level. If the finance manager leaves, their AI productivity leaves with them. Benefits don't compound across the organisation.
Typical engagement: Tool rollout, enablement program, use-case libraries. Weeks to months. Modest cost.
Stage 2 — AI as Accelerator
What it looks like: AI is embedded into specific processes to speed them up. The process still runs the way it always did, but AI compresses the slow steps. Proposal generation that took three days takes four hours. Month-end commentary that took two days takes half a day. Customer email triage that took a morning takes an hour.
Value created: Process cycle time compression. Throughput increase. Faster decisions because inputs arrive faster.
What the business needs: Process mapping, human-in-the-loop design, quality checks, one or two purpose-configured tools per process (often Claude Projects, Custom GPTs, or SaaS products with AI features configured to the business context).
Limitations: AI is still reactive — it waits to be invoked. The business still decides when and how to use it. Value is real but bounded by the number of processes you've explicitly targeted.
Typical engagement: Process-by-process deployment. Success measured in cycle time and hours returned. This is where most serious AI consulting work lives today.
Stage 3 — AI as Automator
What it looks like: AI starts running tasks end-to-end with minimal human involvement for well-defined work. Invoices arrive, get read, get coded, get routed for approval, and land in the accounting system — with humans only handling exceptions. Customer emails get classified, drafted, and queued for review. Weekly reports generate themselves from underlying data.
This is where lightweight integration starts — file watchers, email ingestion, RPA, scheduled exports/imports. Not deep systems integration, but enough to let the AI act without a human clicking the button each time.
Value created: Headcount leverage at scale. Error reduction through consistent execution. 24/7 operation — work happens overnight and on weekends. Cost-to-serve drops measurably.
What the business needs: Defined exception-handling processes, audit trails, monitoring, a governance model for what AI is allowed to do autonomously, and someone accountable for each automated process. This is where the "four enablers" framing really earns its keep — especially the process enabler.
Limitations: Still task-bound. AI does the task well but doesn't notice that the task itself might be the wrong thing to be doing. Automations can silently drift — the process keeps running even when the business context has changed.
Typical engagement: Custom tools, lightweight integration work, governance frameworks. This is where the standalone AI tool stack becomes genuinely relevant. Months to a year. Material investment, material return.
Stage 4 — AI as Operator (the Intelligent Layer)
What it looks like: AI becomes a layer across the business that monitors, flags, recommends, and acts within defined boundaries. It doesn't just process what's put in front of it — it watches for things that matter and surfaces them. Anomalies in spend get flagged before month-end, not after. Customer sentiment shifts get noticed in real time. Sales pipeline risk gets identified before the quarter closes. Stock discrepancies get predicted before the count.
This is what people mean when they say "AI agents," though the term is overused. The defining shift is from reactive (AI waits) to proactive (AI watches and initiates).
Value created: Decisions get made with better information, faster. Problems get caught earlier, when they're cheaper to fix. Leadership attention gets directed to what actually matters rather than what's loudest. The business starts running on earlier, better signals.
What the business needs: Genuinely connected data — the AI needs something to watch. This is where the earlier modernisation and integration work pays off. Clear definition of what the AI is allowed to do autonomously versus what it must escalate. Trust built up from Stages 2 and 3. A culture that acts on AI-generated signals rather than ignoring them.
Limitations: Requires organisational trust in AI outputs that only comes from successful lower stages. Requires data infrastructure many businesses don't have. Genuinely new risks around automated decision-making that need governance.
Typical engagement: Multi-quarter programs. Requires data foundation work, agent design, governance design, and significant change management. This is the conversation that justifies a transformation-scale engagement.
Stage 5 — AI as Operating Model
What it looks like: AI isn't a layer on top of the business — it's part of how the business is designed to run. New processes are designed with AI embedded from the start. Org charts include AI as a capability, not just a tool. Product and service offerings are built around what AI makes possible. Competitive strategy is shaped by AI-enabled capabilities competitors can't match.
This isn't "AI-first" as a slogan. It's the point where removing AI would require redesigning the business, because the business has been built around what AI enables.
Value created: Strategic advantage. Offerings competitors can't match. Cost structures competitors can't match. Capabilities that let the business enter markets or segments that previously weren't viable.
What the business needs: Leadership vision, sustained investment, willingness to redesign rather than retrofit, and the organisational capability built up through Stages 1–4.
Limitations: Not appropriate or necessary for every business. Most SMEs don't need to reach here. Most enterprises will reach here eventually but shouldn't try to skip stages.
Typical engagement: Enterprise strategy, not a consulting project. Years, not months.
How the stages actually stack
Three things are worth making explicit when you present this to a leader:
Stages aren't mutually exclusive — they're cumulative. A mature business operates across multiple stages simultaneously. Individuals still use AI as an assistant (Stage 1) while specific processes are accelerated (Stage 2) while core transactional work is automated (Stage 3) while intelligent oversight watches across all of it (Stage 4). The maturity isn't about reaching Stage 5 — it's about having the right stage present where it matters.
You can't skip stages successfully. Businesses that try to jump from Stage 1 to Stage 4 — buying agent platforms before they've proven process-level value — almost always fail. The organisational muscle for trusting AI is built stage by stage. Leaders need to see this, because the market is full of vendors selling Stage 4 to businesses that aren't ready for Stage 2.
Each stage has a different dominant constraint. Stage 1 is constrained by user adoption. Stage 2 is constrained by process clarity. Stage 3 is constrained by governance and exception handling. Stage 4 is constrained by data foundation and organisational trust. Stage 5 is constrained by leadership vision. Diagnosing which constraint dominates tells you what to work on next.
The sales conversation this unlocks
Once you have this model, the sales dialogue changes. You walk into a client meeting and instead of pitching a use case, you run a diagnostic:
"Let me show you how we think about AI maturity. There are five stages. Most businesses we work with are somewhere between Stage 1 and Stage 2 — they've got individuals using tools well, and they're starting to embed AI into a few processes. Where do you think you are?"
The client self-locates. Usually conservatively — they'll say Stage 1 when they're actually early Stage 2, which is fine. Then you ask:
"What would it mean for your business to reach the next stage reliably in the next 12 months? Not every function, but the two or three that matter most?"
Now you're having a conversation about a journey, not a purchase. And the journey has structure: diagnose current state, identify highest-value next-stage opportunities, build the enablers that stage requires, deliver and measure, then repeat for the next stage. That's a multi-year client relationship, not a one-off project.
The phrase that frames the whole model
When you present this to a leadership team, the line that tends to land is:

"AI isn't a destination, it's a staircase. Each stage creates real value, each stage prepares the business for the next, and skipping stages is how AI programs fail. Our job is to help you climb deliberately — value at every step, trust compounding along the way, and the business genuinely capable of operating at each new level before you move to the next."

That sentence does three things at once: it gives them a mental model they can use in internal conversations, it positions you as a guide rather than a vendor, and it implicitly reframes AI from a technology purchase to an organisational capability — which is a much larger and more defensible engagement footprint.
Where this takes the Thakral One positioning
Practically, having this maturity model means your firm can offer a coherent portfolio at each stage rather than a grab-bag of AI services:
At Stage 1, you sell enablement — licenses, training, champions programs, prompt libraries.
At Stage 2, you sell process acceleration — targeted tool deployment, human-in-the-loop design, outcome measurement.
At Stage 3, you sell automation — custom tools, lightweight integration, governance frameworks.
At Stage 4, you sell the intelligent layer — agent design, data foundation work, organisational trust-building.
At Stage 5, you sell strategy — AI-embedded operating model design, executive advisory.
Each stage has its own pricing model, its own deliverables, and its own success metrics. A client might engage you for Stage 2 work this year, Stage 3 next year, and bring you back for Stage 4 two years after that. That's the firm trajectory — and it's defensible because it's built on a genuine logical progression, not on selling whatever's fashionable this quarter.

